{{Infobox cricket team | team_name = Suffolk county cricket teams | image = | caption = | home_venue = [[Cemetry Road|Field Lane, Bury St Edmunds]] | established = {{circa|1764}} | last_match = 1859 | notable_players = }}
'''Suffolk county cricket teams''' were the teams that represented the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Suffolk]] before the first official formation of [[Suffolk County Cricket Club]] in 1864.
==18th century== Cricket had probably reached Suffolk by the end of the 17th century. The earliest known reference to cricket in Suffolk was in 1743.<ref>Bowen, p.263</ref><ref name="MIS">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Teams/0/342/Other_Matches.html|title=Other Matches played by Suffolk|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> The first mention of a Suffolk representative team is in 1764, with Suffolk playing against [[Norfolk county cricket teams|Norfolk]] at Bury St Edmunds racecourse (today the location of [[RAF Bury St Edmunds|Rougham Airfield]]) on 23 August. Norfolk won this match, which was reported in the ''[[Daily Gazetteer|Gazetteer & London Daily Advertiser]]'' on Tuesday 28 August.<ref>Buckley, p.43</ref> Suffolk played two further matches against Norfolk on 10 and 12 September at [[Scole|Scole, Norfolk]].<ref name="MIS"/>
==19th century== A team representative of Suffolk is next recorded as playing in 1827 against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]].<ref name="MIS"/> It was during this time that the Bury St Edmunds club became prominent, its reputation enhanced when [[Fuller Pilch]] joined in 1824. It was the Bury Club, as it was often called,<ref>ACS, ''Important Matches, pp. 14–15.</ref> playing under the name of Suffolk, that played two [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important matches]] against Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) in 1830, one at [[Lord's]] and the other at [[Cemetry Road|Field Lane, Bury St Edmunds]].<ref name="FCM">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Teams/0/342/First-Class_Matches.html|title=First-Class Matches played by Suffolk|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> The teams won one match each. The team was sometimes called Bury St Edmunds and sometimes Suffolk. In 1847, Suffolk played two more important matches against MCC, again played at Lord's and Field Lane.<ref name="FCM"/> This time, MCC won both matches by large margins. Teams representative of Suffolk continued to play minor matches until at least 1859, when an [[Non-international England cricket teams|All-England Eleven]] played the county.<ref name="MIS"/> The original [[Suffolk County Cricket Club]] was formed on 27 July 1864, becoming representative of Suffolk as a traditional county. It was reconstituted in 1932. It has always fielded a [[Minor counties of English and Welsh cricket|minor counties team]].
The following is a list of matches played by Bury St Edmunds or Suffolk from 1821 to 1859; those marked with {{dagger}} are definitely minor fixtures while the majority are potentially important matches depending on their treatments by different sources:{{fact|date=September 2017}}
